  "prompt": "Can I apply for an E-2 visa while my green card is on process?",
  "response": "Applying for an E-2 visa while your green card application is in process can be complex due to the differing intentions associated with each visa type. The E-2 visa is a non-immigrant visa for investors and requires the applicant to intend to return to their home country upon the visa\u2019s expiration. Conversely, a green card application signifies an intention to immigrate permanently to the United States.\n\nWhen your green card application is pending, it may raise concerns about your true intentions in the U.S. if you apply for a non-immigrant visa like the E-2. U.S. immigration authorities might question whether you genuinely intend to leave the U.S. after your E-2 visa expires since you also have a pending immigrant petition.\n\nHowever, it is not impossible to hold both intentions simultaneously, but it requires careful handling. It is crucial to clearly demonstrate the temporary intent required for the E-2 visa while maintaining your green card process.\n\nConsulting with an immigration attorney is highly recommended to navigate this situation appropriately and to ensure that your applications are not jeopardized. They can provide tailored advice based on your specific circumstances and help you present your case effectively to U.S. immigration authorities.",
